Hepatitis - Russia & Belarus: update, 18 Dec 2000 20001218.2218
Hepatitis - Russia (North Ossetia) 20001204.2111
Date: Tue 13 Feb 2001 14:33:08 +0300
From: A. Vladyko <vladyko@ns.briem.ac.by>
Source: Official information from the Website of the Health Ministry of the
Russian Federation (Outbreaks News Website, in Russian), 23 Jan 2001 [edited
<http://www.depart.drugreg.ru/hotline/>

Hepatitis A - Russia (Moscow province)
--------------------------------------
(1) Between 29 Dec 2000 and 22 Jan 2001 a hepatitis A virus outbreak was
recorded in the City of Serpukhov, Moscow province (Oblast). There were 173
cases; of these 17 were children under 14 years of age, and the remainder
between 19 and 35 years of age. All the infected individuals were admitted
to hospital. Serious cases were not observed. [On 29 Jan 2001, according to
an Information News Website , report on 2 Feb 2001,
the Department of the State Sanitary and Epidemiology Surveillance of the
Russian Federation reported that 183 people had been hospitalized with a
diagnosis of hepatitis A virus infection in Serpukhov city. The source of
infection was [contaminated drinking water. Regular chlorine treatment was
instituted at 4 water intake networks as well as [overhall of plumbing and
sewer system. Authorities plan to install 6 germicide plants at the
artesian wells. Special immunoglobulin prophylaxis and routine vaccination
have been implemented.
(2) Between 25 Dec 2000 and 21 Jan 2001 in the City of Protvino, Moscow
Oblast, a total of 55 cases (including 8 children under 14 years of age) of
hepatitis A virus infection has been recorded. All the affected individuals
were admitted to hospital. The disease course ranged from mild to
moderately serious. The water supply in Protivno is taken from artesian
wells tapping the same aquifer that also supplies the city of Serpukhov.
The quality of drinking water in Protivno was [also unsatisfactory.
Specialists from the State Sanitary and Epidemiology Centers in Serpukhov
Ristrict and Moscow Oblast are carrying out an epidemiological investigation.
